    teaching: `Sīla — moral virtue — is the first of the three trainings (sikkhā): sīla, samādhi, paññā. It is not the least of the three. It is the foundation without which the other two cannot stand. The Sāmaññaphala Sutta (DN 2) describes sīla as the cool shade in which samādhi can grow. Without it, the mind is like a field of rocks — effort will be wasted.\n\nThe five precepts (pañcasīla) are training rules (sikkhāpada), not commandments issued by an external authority. They are undertaken voluntarily, with understanding. Each precept is a choice to not act in a way that harms oneself or others — a repeated, deliberate turning away from akusala.\n\nSīla produces passaddhi — tranquility, stillness, ease. When conduct is clean, there is no reservoir of remorse for the mind to draw on. Guilt and agitation lose their fuel. This ease is not merely pleasant — it is the proximate cause of samādhi. The Visuddhimagga begins its entire path with sīla because there is nowhere else to begin.\n\nBegin here. Not once, but again and again — each morning, each evening, each time a precept has been broken. Renewal of sīla is itself a practice.`,
