    teaching: `Mettā — loving-kindness — is the direct antidote to byāpāda. In MN 21 (Kakacūpama Sutta), the Buddha sets the standard: even if bandits were to cut you limb from limb, the one who let hatred arise would not be following his teaching. The mind of mettā, he says, should be like space — it cannot be painted on, carved into, or ruined.\n\nMettā is not sentiment. It is a trained mental quality — a deliberate, repeated extension of goodwill that, over time, leaves no room for ill-will to take root. The Metta Sutta (Sn 1.8) describes its scope: all beings without exception — seen and unseen, near and far, born and to be born. None excluded.\n\nThe near enemy of mettā is affectionate attachment (pema) — it looks similar but has a different texture. Pema is selective; mettā is boundless. Pema depends on the other being likable; mettā does not. The far enemy is byāpāda — hatred — which mettā directly dissolves.\n\nThe practice begins with oneself. This is often skipped or dismissed, but it is not optional. One who has not learned to extend genuine goodwill toward oneself will have a hollow practice when extending it to others.`,
