            teaching: `Ānāpānasati — mindfulness of breathing — is the most widely taught entry point into kāyānupassanā and, in MN 118, the Buddha presents it as a complete path organized into sixteen steps across four tetrads. The first tetrad covers the body, the second feeling tones, the third the mind, and the fourth mental objects — the four satipatthānas in sequence, all accessed through the single object of the breath.\n\nThe instruction is simple and profound: knowing when the breath is long, knowing when it is short, experiencing the whole body, calming the bodily formation. The breath is always available. It cannot be left behind. It is the most portable object of meditation that exists.`,
