            sutta: "MN 10",
            teaching: `Sampajañña — clear comprehension — accompanies sati as its functional dimension. Where sati knows what is present, sampajañña knows the purpose, suitability, and non-delusion of activity. MN 10 lists the range: going forward and returning, looking ahead and sideways, bending and stretching, wearing robes, eating, drinking, chewing, tasting, attending to the calls of nature, walking, standing, sitting, falling asleep, waking, speaking, and remaining silent.\n\nSampajañña asks, of each action: Is this appropriate? Is this suitable? Is this free from delusion? Not as a constant critical evaluation, but as the background quality of a mind that knows what it is doing and why.`,
