            sutta: "MN 10 §§14–21",
            teaching: `MN 10 sections 14–21 present the charnel ground contemplations — a series of reflections on the stages of decomposition of the body after death. In the Buddha's time, charnel grounds were accessible places where the dead were left exposed, and practitioners would actually go and contemplate the stages of decay directly. Today the practice is primarily one of guided reflection.\n\nThe stages move from a recently dead body, through the stages of bloating, discoloration, and festering; then to bones — first with flesh and blood, then denuded; then scattered, whitened, and finally crumbled to powder. After each stage, the practitioner applies the refrain: 'This body too is of the same nature. It will become like this. It has not escaped this.'\n\nThe purpose is not morbidity. It is liberation from the excessive identification with the body as permanent, solid, and self. When the ending is clearly seen, the present moment of aliveness is more clearly valued. Maraṇasati — mindfulness of death — is the companion to this practice.`,
