        teaching: `Vedanānupassanā — contemplation of feeling tones — is the second foundation. Vedanā is not emotion. It is the bare affective quality that accompanies every moment of experience: pleasant (sukha), unpleasant (dukkha), or neither-pleasant-nor-unpleasant (adukkha-asukha). Every contact with a sense object — sight, sound, smell, taste, touch, mental object — is accompanied by one of these three feeling tones.\n\nVedanā is the hinge between contact and craving in the chain of dependent origination: phassa → vedanā → taṇhā. When a pleasant vedanā arises, craving arises — wanting more, wanting it to continue. When an unpleasant vedanā arises, aversion arises — wanting it to stop, wanting it gone. When a neutral vedanā arises, delusion arises — the mind slides into unawareness, boredom, disconnection.\n\nThe practice of vedanānupassanā is to intercept the chain at this hinge point. Not by suppressing vedanā — it cannot be suppressed — but by knowing it clearly before craving has a chance to arise. 'This is pleasant.' 'This is unpleasant.' 'This is neutral.' The knowing itself, held without grasping or aversion, breaks the automatic momentum from vedanā to taṇhā.\n\nThe Buddha taught that one who sees vedanā clearly is like an archer who has learned to stop the arrow in flight — intercepting the chain before it becomes suffering.`,
