        teaching: `Cittānupassanā — contemplation of mind states — is the third foundation. MN 10 lists sixteen pairs of mind states that the practitioner learns to know clearly: mind with lust / without lust; with hatred / without hatred; with delusion / without delusion; contracted / scattered; exalted / not exalted; surpassable / unsurpassable; concentrated / not concentrated; liberated / not liberated.\n\nThe practice is not self-criticism. A practitioner who observes 'the mind has lust' is not confessing a failure — they are doing precisely what the Sutta asks. The instruction is to know what is present: 'one knows a mind with lust as a mind with lust.' The knowing is neutral. The state is simply named and seen.\n\nThis is described in one Dhamma tradition as the practice of the weatherman: a good weatherman does not take credit for sunshine or blame for rain. They simply report what is present. Cittānupassanā is the development of this quality of impartial knowing toward one's own mental weather.\n\nOver time, this practice produces a profound shift: the mind states are seen as arising and passing conditions, not as expressions of a fixed self. The practitioner who has spent years identifying with 'I am an angry person' begins to see: anger arises, anger passes. The 'I' that claimed ownership of it is not found.`,
