        teaching: `Dhammānupassanā — contemplation of mental objects or mind-objects — is the fourth foundation, and in some ways the most comprehensive. Where the previous three foundations observe body, feeling, and mind as objects, the fourth observes the structures through which the mind constructs and interprets experience: the five hindrances, the five aggregates, the six sense spheres, the seven factors of awakening, and the four noble truths.\n\nThe fourth foundation is, in essence, the investigation of how the mind builds the sense of a world and a self out of raw experience. Through the lens of dhammānupassanā, the meditator does not just observe what is present — they observe the frameworks the mind is using, and see those frameworks themselves as arising and passing phenomena.\n\nThis is the dimension of satipatthāna closest to vipassanā in its classical sense: the direct seeing of the three characteristics (anicca, dukkha, anattā) operating in the structures of experience itself. The hindrances are seen as arising and passing. The aggregates are seen as not-self. The factors of awakening are seen as capable of being cultivated or allowing to decline. The Four Noble Truths are seen not as concepts but as living realities.`,
